h3. Summary
The following custom CSS styling applied to the sidebar within the *Sidebar, header and footer* under the *Look and feel* section used to work on older versions of Confluence, such as Confluence 1000.340.2. However, it doesn't work anymore on newer versions of Confluence:
{code}{style}
p{
font-family: "Open Sans", Tahoma;
}

#space-favourite-add {
display:none !important;
}

.ia-secondary-header span {
visibility:hidden;
display:inline;
}

.acs-side-bar{
background-color: #313131;
}

.plugin_pagetree_current{
color: white;
}

.space-tools-section{
background-color: #313131;
}

{style}{code}


h3. Environment
Cloud - Confluence 1000.403.0

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Open a space
# Go to *Space tools* > *Look and feel*
# Go to *Sidebar, header and footer*
# Apply custom CSS to it


h3. Expected Results
The styling should be render as it used to.

h3. Actual Results
Nothing happens on the space styling.

*(Please, see attachment)*

h3. Problem Definition
When importing a Word into Confluence, I would need that the text is auto-inserted into a Code Block Macro.
What is being asked for, is some technique, process, or workaround by which we can most efficiently designate a block of text as something that should belong to a code block macro.

h3. Suggested Solution
 For example:
· A way to designate in the source Word document that a block of text should be converted to a Code Block macro;
· Tools in Confluence that can edit the raw markup;
· Any kind of scripting tool or macro-recording/playback in Confluence that would reduce the tedium of manually selecting text and converting it to a code block;
